                marked('Therefore create physical and virtual spaces where the experience of individuals, both customers and staff, can be shared as stories. Stories are narratives of an experience as it was experienced, rather than models such as user stories, use cases, value-chain diagrams, or business process descriptions. Staff are trained to narrate stories in a medium of their choice (text, audio, or video) of their work experience that are descriptive and interesting with a balance of criticism and appreciation. Individuals are encouraged to share their experiences as much as possible in open social networks (physical and virtual) without fear of repercussion or adverse consequences, either using their own names or anonymously. Managers and leaders become responsible for organizing the physical and virtual spaces for gathering stories. They also catalog and categorizing stories in clusters so that the rest of the organization can access, process, and understand the exact nature of work and challenges faced by the customers and staff on a daily basis. The correlation of stories to changes is made visible in the same physical and virtual spaces. The applications used by support staff have features for open feedback freely accessible by other staff. Analysts, designers, and developers have ready access to operational staff to understand the nature of their work and propose, prototype, and introduce changes facilitated by the managers and leaders who organize the physical and virtual spaces for those staff. Analysts can add their artifacts, such as their interpreted requirements, designs, prioritizations, and analysis in the same physical and virtual spaces as the stories. Workload is openly visible to others, and managers and leaders can choose to have either dedicated moments and spaces for organization-wide interactions or be open for them to occur at any time. Similarly applications provided to customers have clear methods to provide feedback to the people who build the applications. The most passionate customers are nurtured as product ambassadors and developed as an extended part of the organization.');
